Reference - Authors: B L Talken; K R Schäfermeyer; C W Bailey; D R Lee; R W Hoffman
Reference - Title: T cell epitope mapping of the Smith antigen reveals that highly conserved Smith antigen motifs are the dominant target of T cell immunity in systemic lupus erythematosus.
Epitope - Source Molecule: Small nuclear ribonucleoprotein-associated proteins B and B'
Epitope - Molecule Parent: Small nuclear ribonucleoprotein-associated proteins B and B'
Epitope - Epitope Comments: Alanine scanning shows that amino acids Ile1, Leu2,  Asp4, Gly5, Arg6 and Ile9 are critical for MHC binding or TCR interaction. Also known as Small nuclear ribonucleoprotein associated proteins B (snRNP-B), forms part of the Smith Antigen (Sm) complex.
Immunization - Comments: T cell clones derived from PBMC of SLE patients were stimulated and cloned with different peptides and used to asses the reactivity against Sm antigen proteins.
Assay - Comments: 4 T cell clones derived from 1 SLE patient were shown. Truncation of the sequence RMRCILQDGRIFIGT was used to define the minimal epitope.
Assay Antigen - Source Molecule: Small nuclear ribonucleoprotein-associated proteins B and B'
Assay Antigen - Molecule Parent: Small nuclear ribonucleoprotein-associated proteins B and B'

Reference - Authors: Rikke Baek Sørensen; Mikkel Faurschou; Lone Troelsen; David Schrama; Søren Jacobsen; Jürgen C Becker; Per Thor Straten; Mads Hald Andersen
Reference - Title: Melanoma inhibitor of apoptosis protein (ML-IAP) specific cytotoxic T lymphocytes cross-react with an epitope from the auto-antigen SS56.
Immunization - Comments: Blood samples were collected from patients with systemic lupus erythematosus (diagnosed according to the classification criteria for SLE of Tan et al). The auto-antibody status of the SLE patients was as follows: 7/20 positive for anti-SSA/Ro, 2/20 positive for anti-SSB/La, 17/20 positive for anti- ANA og 12/20 positive for anti-DNA.
Assay - Comments: In situ staining also revealed epitope-reactive T cells in skin lesions of SLE patients.

Reference - Authors: Zev M Sthoeger; Amir Sharabi; Yair Molad; Ilan Asher; Heidy Zinger; Molly Dayan; Edna Mozes
Reference - Title: Treatment of lupus patients with a tolerogenic peptide, hCDR1 (Edratide): immunomodulation of gene expression.
Related Object - Object Type: Fragment of a Natural Sequence Molecule
2nd in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to prevent or reduce disease
2nd immunogen - Dose Schedule: 0.5, 1, or 2.5 mg given weekly for 24 weeks
Immunization - Comments: The study consisted of 9 patients with SLE. All patients had antinuclear antibodies and anti-dsDNA autoantibodies in their sera at study entry. The mean SLEDAI-2K and BILAG scores, determined for all patients at entry to the study (week 0), were 8.2 ± 2.5 (range 6–12) and 7.8 ± 2.4 (range 4–13), respectively, indicating mild to moderate SLE. Seven patients were treated with Hydroxychloroquine (400 mg/day) and seven with oral corticosteroids (mean daily dose of prednisone 18.2 ± 11.3 mg; range 5–40). Patients were treated with the epitope to reduce SLE.
Assay - Comments: Treatment with the epitope resulted in clinical improvement. The mean BILAG score of the epitope-treated patients decreased significantly, whereas the change in the BILAG score in the placebo-treated group was not significant. Similarly, the mean SLEDAI-2K score decreased significantly in the epitope-treated patients, compared with an insignificant change in the placebo-treated patients. In epitope-treated patients, the expression of IL-1ß, TNF-α, IFN-γ, and IL-10 decreased significantly.

Reference - Authors: Fanny Monneaux; José Manuel Lozano; Manuel E Patarroyo; Jean-Paul Briand; Sylviane Muller
Reference - Title: T cell recognition and therapeutic effect of a phosphorylated synthetic peptide of the 70K snRNP protein administered in MR/lpr mice.
2nd in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to prevent or reduce disease
2nd immunogen - Dose Schedule: Three doses of 100 µg at a two week interval and one dose of 100 µg four weeks later.
Immunization - Comments: Mice were immunized with the epitope to treat lupus.
Assay - Comments: Mice treated with the epitope had less severe lupus as measured by survival (to 38 weeks), proteinuria and anti DNA anitbodies.  Mice treated with the epitope did not start to die until 22 weeks while mice treated with saline started to die at 15 weeks.

2nd immunogen - Dose Schedule: Four doses of 100 µg at a two-week interval.

Reference - Authors: S Langer; D Langnickel; P Enghard; R Undeutsch; G R Burmester; F Hiepe; A Radbruch; G Riemekasten
Reference - Title: The systemic and SmD183-119-autoantigen-specific cytokine memory of Th cells in SLE patients.
Immunization - Comments: Blood samples were obtained from 37 patients with SLE.  Most of the patients received immunosuppressive drugs (14 received azathioprine, three cyclophosphamide, four mycophenolate, six hydroxychloroquine, two methotrexate, one leflunomide, one ciclosporin-A, and three patients had a combination of two different immunosuppressive drugs). Two patients received steroids in a dosage >10 mg/day.
Assay - Comments: TNFa production was higher in SLE patients than in healthy subjects.  The increase in frequencies of TNF-a expressing Th cells upon expansion and activation of epitope-specific memory Th cells was also associated with serum anti-dsDNA antibody levels in the corresponding donor.

Reference - Authors: S Langer; D Langnickel; P Enghard; R Undeutsch; G R Burmester; F Hiepe; A Radbruch; G Riemekasten
Reference - Title: The systemic and SmD183-119-autoantigen-specific cytokine memory of Th cells in SLE patients.
Immunization - Comments: Blood samples were obtained from 37 patients with SLE.  Most of the patients received immunosuppressive drugs (14 received azathioprine, three cyclophosphamide, four mycophenolate, six hydroxychloroquine, two methotrexate, one leflunomide, one ciclosporin-A, and three patients had a combination of two different immunosuppressive drugs). Two patients received steroids in a dosage >10 mg/day.
Assay - Comments: SLE patients showed a decreased frequency of IL-10 producing T cells compared with healthy controls only after stimulation with the epitope.  An increased frequency in epitope-specific T-cells expressing IL-10 was associated with disease activity and low anti-epitope and anti-dsDNA autoantibody levels in culture supernatants.

Reference - Authors: S Langer; D Langnickel; P Enghard; R Undeutsch; G R Burmester; F Hiepe; A Radbruch; G Riemekasten

Reference - Title: Phenotypic and functional analysis of EBV-specific memory CD8 cells in SLE.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Exposure with existing immune reactivity without evidence for disease

Assay - Comments: Tetramer positive CD8 cells were phenotypically in early to intermediate differentiation state (CD27+/CD28+ or CD27+/CD28-, CCR7+ or CCR7-, CD57-) and displayed the phenotype of resting memory cells. Reference - Title: T cell reactivity against the SmD1(83-119) C terminal peptide in patients with systemic lupus erythematosus.

Reference - Authors: Fanny Monneaux; Johan Hoebeke; Christelle Sordet; Céline Nonn; Jean-Paul Briand; Bernard Maillère; Jean Sibillia; Sylviane Muller
Reference - Title: Selective modulation of CD4+ T cells from lupus patients by a promiscuous, protective peptide analog.
Immunization - Comments: SLE patients were treated by low doses of methotrexate, hydroxychloroquine, and/or nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs.  Excluded from the series of patients enrolled in this study were all patients who received prolonged and  heavy suppressive treatments.
Assay - Comments: Peptide analog P140 containing a phosphorylated serine at position 10 did not induce proliferation in any patient's PBMCs.  Epitope-specific proliferation was also measured by CFSE assays and dot blot analysis and similar results were obtained.
MHC Restriction - Evidence Code: T cell assay -T cell subset identification

Reference - Authors: Fanny Monneaux; Johan Hoebeke; Christelle Sordet; Céline Nonn; Jean-Paul Briand; Bernard Maillère; Jean Sibillia; Sylviane Muller
Reference - Title: Selective modulation of CD4+ T cells from lupus patients by a promiscuous, protective peptide analog.
Immunization - Comments: SLE patients were treated by low doses of methotrexate, hydroxychloroquine, and/or nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs.
Assay - Comments: Peptide analog P140 containing a phosphorylated serine at position 10 induced IL-10 secretion in 8 of 16 SLE patient's PBMCs.   As compared with IL-10 secretion levels induced by phosphorylated peptide P140, those induced by the unmodified epitope tested in parallel were equivalent or lower.
MHC Restriction - Evidence Code: T cell assay -T cell subset identification

Reference - Title: T cell reactivity to MHC class II-bound self peptides in systemic lupus erythematosus-prone MRL/lpr mice.
Immunization - Comments: Unprimed MLR/lpr, C3H/HeJ and B6.H2k mice were used.  MLR/lpr mice ranging from 1- to 5-month-old were also used.

Reference - Authors: B H Hahn; R R Singh; W K Wong; B P Tsao; K Bulpitt; F M Ebling
Reference - Title: Treatment with a consensus peptide based on amino acid sequences in autoantibodies prevents T cell activation by autoantigens and delays disease onset in murine lupus.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: This artificial peptide was constructed based on an algorithm that defines the T cell stimulatory amino acid sequences from the VH regions of multiple BWF1 IgG antibodies to DNA.
Related Object - Object Type: Fragment of a Natural Sequence Molecule
2nd in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to prevent or reduce disease
2nd immunogen - Dose Schedule: Monthy injections of 1000 µg of epitope starting at age of 10 weeks or 20 weeks
Immunization - Comments: Survival of epitope-treated mice were compared with control mice.
Assay - Comments: Treatment with the epitope resulted in reduced symptoms of Lupus.  Treated mice showed prolonged survival, reduced plasma IFN-g and IL-4 levels, no increase in plasma IgG levels that characterized spontaneous disease, and reduced the levels of autoantibodies such as anti-double-stranded DNA Ab, anti-nucleosome Ab, and anti-cardiolipin Ab.

Reference - Title: Clinical amelioration of murine lupus by a peptide based on the complementarity determining region-1 of an autoantibody and by cyclophosphamide: similarities and differences in the mechanisms of action.
2nd in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to prevent or reduce disease
2nd immunogen - Dose Schedule: Up to 12 weekly doses of 25 µg.
Immunization - Comments: Mice were treated with the epitope to reduce severity of SLE.  Some mice were also given IP doses of cyclophasphamide monohydrate.
Assay - Comments: Mice immunized with the epitope developed less severe SLE as measured by anti-dsDNA antibodies, proteinuria, and immune complex deposits.

Reference - Authors: A Kaliyaperumal; C Mohan; W Wu; S K Datta
Reference - Title: Nucleosomal peptide epitopes for nephritis-inducing T helper cells of murine lupus.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to cause disease
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 100 µg, 3 booster injections at 2-week intervals of 50 µu
Immunization - Comments: Mice were immunized with the epitope to induce SLE.
Assay - Comments: By 40 weeks of age, 100% of mice immunized with the epitope developed severe lupus nephritis. Histopathology revealed a 3+ to 4+ grade of nephritis. The levels of IgG autoantibodies specific for ssDNA, dsDNA, and nucleosomes were significantly elevated in mice immunized with the epitope compared to control mice at 21 weeks of age; at 30 weeks and beyond, there was no difference.

Reference - Authors: Hee-Kap Kang; Michael Liu; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: Low-dose peptide tolerance therapy of lupus generates plasmacytoid dendritic cells that cause expansion of autoantigen-specific regulatory T cells and contraction of inflammatory Th17 cells.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence was from the cited reference: Kang, H. K. et al. 2005. J. Immunol. 174: 3247-3255. [PMID: 15749855].
Immunization - Comments: T cell hybridoma was generated by fusing CD4 enriched T cells from the mice with the TCR α/ß-chain-negative variant of the BW5147 thymoma. The details of the T Cell clone production was described in the cited reference:Adams S. et al. Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA 88: 11271 [PMID: 1837146].
Assay - Comments: Splenic DCs from the mice injected with the epitope presented the epitope to the epitope-specific T cell hybridoma more efficiently than B cells from the same mice. Peak stimulatory ability was seen at 24 hour post-injection.

Reference - Authors: Hee-Kap Kang; Michael Liu; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: Low-dose peptide tolerance therapy of lupus generates plasmacytoid dendritic cells that cause expansion of autoantigen-specific regulatory T cells and contraction of inflammatory Th17 cells.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence was from the cited reference: Kang, H. K. et al. 2005. J. Immunol. 174: 3247-3255. [PMID: 15749855].
2nd immunogen - Dose Schedule: 3 doses of 1 ug, administered at intervals of 2 weeks.
Assay - Comments: The epitope induced tolerance to the epitope as measured by reduced IL-17.
MHC Restriction - Evidence Code: T cell assay -T cell subset identification

Reference - Authors: Hee-Kap Kang; Michael Liu; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: Low-dose peptide tolerance therapy of lupus generates plasmacytoid dendritic cells that cause expansion of autoantigen-specific regulatory T cells and contraction of inflammatory Th17 cells.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence was from the cited reference: Kang, H. K. et al. 2005. J. Immunol. 174: 3247-3255. [PMID: 15749855].

Reference - Authors: Arunan Kaliyaperumal; Marissa A Michaels; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: Naturally processed chromatin peptides reveal a major autoepitope that primes pathogenic T and B cells of lupus.
Immunization - Comments: Nucleosome-specific T cell clones were derived from SNF1 mice with lupus nephritis. The details of the immunization procedure were not described.

Reference - Authors: Arunan Kaliyaperumal; Marissa A Michaels; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: Naturally processed chromatin peptides reveal a major autoepitope that primes pathogenic T and B cells of lupus.
Immunization - Comments: Nucleosome-specific T cell clones were derived from SNF1 mice with lupus nephritis. The details of the immunization procedure were not described.
Assay - Comments: Incubation of the nucleosome-specific T cell clones with the epitope and freshly isolated B cells increased the antibody response to histone, nucleosomes, and DNA.

Reference - Authors: Arunan Kaliyaperumal; Marissa A Michaels; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: Naturally processed chromatin peptides reveal a major autoepitope that primes pathogenic T and B cells of lupus.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to cause disease
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 100 µg in CFA, then 3 boosts of 50 µg in alum at 2-week intervals
Immunization - Comments: 12-week old prenephritic SNF1 mice were immunized with the epitope to induce lupus nephritis.
Assay - Comments: Mice immunized with the epitope did not develop lupus nephritis at a rate higher than control mice.

Reference - Authors: Arunan Kaliyaperumal; Marissa A Michaels; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: Naturally processed chromatin peptides reveal a major autoepitope that primes pathogenic T and B cells of lupus.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to cause disease
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 100 µg in CFA, then 3 boosts of 50 µg in alum at 2-week intervals
Immunization - Comments: 12-week old prenephritic SNF1 mice were immunized with the epitope to induce lupus nephritis.
Assay - Comments: Sixty percent of mice immunized with the epitope developed lupus nephritis by week 20, faster than control mice. By week 28, the incidence was similar to control mice.

Reference - Authors: Arunan Kaliyaperumal; Marissa A Michaels; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: Naturally processed chromatin peptides reveal a major autoepitope that primes pathogenic T and B cells of lupus.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to cause disease
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 100 µg in CFA, then 3 boosts of 50 µg in alum at 2-week intervals
Immunization - Comments: 12-week old prenephritic SNF1 mice were immunized with the epitope to induce lupus nephritis.
Assay - Comments: Eighty percent of mice immunized with the epitope developed severe lupus nephritis within 4 weeks, much faster than control mice. By week 28, all immunized mice developed severe lupus nephritis.

Reference - Authors: H Ito; S Matsushita; Y Tokano; H Nishimura; Y Tanaka; S Fujisao; H Mitsuya; H Hashimoto; Y Nishimura
Reference - Title: Analysis of T cell responses to the beta 2-glycoprotein I-derived peptide library in patients with anti-beta 2-glycoprotein I antibody-associated autoimmunity.
Immunization - Comments: A T cell line and clone was derived by in vitro restimulation with a pool of peptide covering the sequence of b2GPI, including a fragment covering the epitope, from PBMCs of an anti-bGPI antibody positive donor  with anti-phospholipid syndrome (APS) secondary to SLE, and a history of cerebral infarction.
Assay - Comments: The minimal epitope recognized by a CD4+ T cell clone was defined by truncations of the fragment 244-264 that reacted with the parental T cell line.

Reference - Authors: H Ito; S Matsushita; Y Tokano; H Nishimura; Y Tanaka; S Fujisao; H Mitsuya; H Hashimoto; Y Nishimura
Reference - Title: Analysis of T cell responses to the beta 2-glycoprotein I-derived peptide library in patients with anti-beta 2-glycoprotein I antibody-associated autoimmunity.
Immunization - Comments: A T cell line and clone was derived by in vitro restimulation with a pool of peptide covering the sequence of b2GPI, including a fragment covering the epitope, from PBMCs of an anti-bGPI antibody positive donor  with anti-phospholipid syndrome (APS) secondary to SLE, and a history of cerebral infarction.
Assay - Comments: The production of IFN-g by the epitope-specific T cell clone was low. The IFN-g/IL-4 ratio of T cell lines or clones derived from APS or SLE patients was significantly lower than for healthy control-derived T cell lines when tested with their respective cognate peptides.

Reference - Title: Analysis of T cell responses to the beta 2-glycoprotein I-derived peptide library in patients with anti-beta 2-glycoprotein I antibody-associated autoimmunity.

Reference - Authors: Amir Sharabi; Molly Dayan; Heidy Zinger; Edna Mozes
Reference - Title: A new model of induced experimental systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) in pigs and its amelioration by treatment with a tolerogenic peptide.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to cause disease
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: Two doses of 20 µg or 100 µg at a three week interval.
2nd in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to prevent or reduce disease
Immunization - Comments: Pigs were immunized with human anti-DNA 16/6Id in CFA to induce systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE).  The first dose was in CFA and the second dose was in PBS.  When pigs developed symptoms, they were treated with the epitope in sulfobutylether beta cyclodextrin.
Assay - Comments: SLE was induced in pigs with the human anti-DNA 16/6Id protein.  SLE was reduced in pigs treated with the epitope as measured by dsDNA specific antibodies, erythrocyte sedimentation rate, immune complex deposits in the kidneys, increased mRNA expression of IL-1ß, TNFα, IFN-gamma, IL-10, and decreased mRNA expression of TGFß, Foxp3 and Bcl-xL.

Reference - Authors: Jürgen W Dieker; Justin H Fransen; Casandra C van Bavel; Jean-Paul Briand; Cor W Jacobs; Sylviane Muller; Jo H Berden; Johan van der Vlag
Reference - Title: Apoptosis-induced acetylation of histones is pathogenic in systemic lupus erythematosus.
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: Four doses of 100 µg at two-week intervals.

Reference - Authors: Jürgen W Dieker; Justin H Fransen; Casandra C van Bavel; Jean-Paul Briand; Cor W Jacobs; Sylviane Muller; Jo H Berden; Johan van der Vlag
Reference - Title: Apoptosis-induced acetylation of histones is pathogenic in systemic lupus erythematosus.
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: Four doses of 100 µg at two-week intervals.

Reference - Authors: Amir Sharabi; Edna Mozes
Reference - Title: The suppression of murine lupus by a tolerogenic peptide involves foxp3-expressing CD8 cells that are required for the optimal induction and function of foxp3-expressing CD4 cells.
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: One dose of 1 µg.
2nd immunogen - Dose Schedule: One or three doses of 50 µg.
Immunization - Comments: Mice were immunized with the human anti-DNA mAb and the epitope from the mAb concomitantly.  The epitope was given to induce tolerance.
Assay - Comments: Administration of the epitope induced tolerence in mice as measured by reduction in proliferation, IL-10 and IFN-gamma in response to 16/6Id and increase in TGF-ß in response to 16/6Id.
MHC Restriction - Evidence Code: T cell assay -T cell subset identification

Reference - Authors: Amir Sharabi; Edna Mozes
Reference - Title: The suppression of murine lupus by a tolerogenic peptide involves foxp3-expressing CD8 cells that are required for the optimal induction and function of foxp3-expressing CD4 cells.
Immunization - Comments: Lupus-prone mice were given the epitope to induce tolerance.
Assay - Comments: Administration of the epitope induced tolerence in mice as measured by reduction in IL-10 and IFN-gamma in response to 16/6Id and increase in TGF-ß in response to 16/6Id.
MHC Restriction - Evidence Code: T cell assay -T cell subset identification

Reference - Authors: Amir Sharabi; Edna Mozes
Reference - Title: The suppression of murine lupus by a tolerogenic peptide involves foxp3-expressing CD8 cells that are required for the optimal induction and function of foxp3-expressing CD4 cells.
2nd in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to prevent or reduce disease
Immunization - Comments: Mice were treated for systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) with the epitope.
Assay - Comments: Mice treated with the epitope developed less severe SLE than mice treated with vehicle as measured by dsDNA antibodies, proteinuria and renal immune complex deposits.
MHC Restriction - Evidence Code: T cell assay -T cell subset identification

Reference - Authors: Dror Luger; Molly Dayan; Heidy Zinger; Jian-Ping Liu; Edna Mozes
Reference - Title: A peptide based on the complementarity determining region 1 of a human monoclonal autoantibody ameliorates spontaneous and induced lupus manifestations in correlation with cytokine immunomodulation.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The peptide was based on the complementarity determining region (CDR) 1 of the human anti-DNA monoclonal antibody that bears the 16/6Id.
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 2 doses of 1 µg, 3 weeks apart
Immunization - Comments: Mice were immunized with the human anti-DNA mAb 16/6Id to induce experimental systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). 3.5 months after the booster injection, which clinical manifestations of lupus were observed, mice were treated with 50, 200, 300 or 400 μg of the epitope in PBS or Captisol (sulfobutylether beta cyclodextrin).
Assay - Comments: Treatment with the epitope induced tolerance to human mAb 16/6Id, as measured by decreased secretion of IFN-γ IL-10 and TNFα and increased secretion of TGFß.

Reference - Authors: N Brosh; H Zinger; M Fridkin; E Mozes
Reference - Title: A peptide based on the sequence of the CDR3 of a murine anti-DNA mAb is a better modulator of experimental SLE than its single amino acid-substituted analogs.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: This epitope is from the CDR of a pathogenic anti-DNA 16/6 Id+ mAb.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to cause disease
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dsoe of 20 ug
Immunization - Comments: Mice were injected with the epitope to cause experiential SLE.
Assay - Comments: The epitope caused an increase in anti-DNA as well as immune complex deposition in the kidneys.  Mutant epitope analogs  with residue substitutions at Ala11 and Nle13 also cause disease.

Reference - Authors: N Brosh; H Zinger; M Fridkin; E Mozes
Reference - Title: A peptide based on the sequence of the CDR3 of a murine anti-DNA mAb is a better modulator of experimental SLE than its single amino acid-substituted analogs.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: This epitope is from the CDR of a pathogenic anti-DNA 16/6 Id+ mAb.
2nd in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to prevent or reduce disease
Immunization - Comments: Mice were injected with the human anti-DNA mAb 16/6 Id which caused experimental SLE. Then the mice were treated with the epitope.
Assay - Comments: The epitope caused a decrease in anti-DNA as well as immune complex deposition in the kidneys.  Mutant epitope analogs with residue substitutions at Ala11 and Nle13 also worked.

Reference - Authors: Hee-Kap Kang; Ming-Yi Chiang; Michael Liu; Diane Ecklund; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: The histone peptide H4 71-94 alone is more effective than a cocktail of peptide epitopes in controlling lupus: immunoregulatory mechanisms.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence was found in the cited reference, Kaliyaperumal et al, J Exp Med: 183(6) 1996 [PMID: 8676066].
2nd in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to prevent or reduce disease
2nd immunogen - Dose Schedule: Doses of 0.37 nM every two weeks.
Immunization - Comments: SNF1 lupus-prone mice that were serologically autoimmune but pre-nephritic were treated with the epitope to treat systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE).
Assay - Comments: Mice treated with the epitope showed reduction in symptoms of SLE including nephritis, antibodies to DNA, nucleosomes and histones, as well as reduced kidney Th17 T cell infiltration.

Reference - Authors: Hee-Kap Kang; Ming-Yi Chiang; Michael Liu; Diane Ecklund; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: The histone peptide H4 71-94 alone is more effective than a cocktail of peptide epitopes in controlling lupus: immunoregulatory mechanisms.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence was found in the cited reference, Kaliyaperumal et al, J Exp Med: 183(6) 1996 [PMID: 8676066].
2nd immunogen - Dose Schedule: Doses of 0.37 nM every two weeks.
Immunization - Comments: SNF1 lupus-prone mice that were serologically autoimmune but pre-nephritic were treated with the epitope to treat systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE).
Assay - Comments: Mice treated with the epitope induced tolerance to nucleosomes as measured by reduction in IFNγ and IL-17 secretion in response to nucleosomes.

Reference - Authors: Jan Broder Engler; Reinmar Undeutsch; Lutz Kloke; Stefan Rosenberger; Marina Backhaus; Udo Schneider; Karl Egerer; Duska Dragun; Jörg Hofmann; Dörte Huscher; Gerd-Rüdiger Burmester; Jens Y Humrich; Philipp Enghard; Gabriela Riemekasten
Reference - Title: Unmasking of autoreactive CD4 T cells by depletion of CD25 regulatory T cells in systemic lupus erythematosus.
Epitope - Source Molecule: Small nuclear ribonucleoprotein Sm D1 (snRNP core protein D1) (Sm-D1) (Sm-D autoantigen)
Immunization - Comments: Blood cells from 38 SLE patients were tested.
Assay - Comments: Simulation with the epitope elicited no T cell response, as detected by intracellular CD154 expression.  When Treg cells were depleted, an increase of response was seen.
MHC Restriction - Evidence Code: T cell assay -T cell subset identification
Assay Antigen - Source Molecule: Small nuclear ribonucleoprotein Sm D1 (snRNP core protein D1) (Sm-D1) (Sm-D autoantigen)

Reference - Authors: Robert Zimmer; Hugo R Scherbarth; Oscar Luis Rillo; Juan Jesus Gomez-Reino; Sylviane Muller
Reference - Title: Lupuzor/P140 peptide in patients with systemic lupus erythematosus: a randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled phase IIb clinical trial.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence is found in Monneaux F et al. Eur J Immunol. 2003 Feb;33(2):287-96 [PMID:12548559].
2nd in vivo Process - Process Type: Administration in vivo to prevent or reduce disease
2nd immunogen - Dose Schedule: 3 doses of 200 ug at an interval of 4 weeks
Immunization - Comments: Adult patients  with an established diagnosis of SLE according to the revised American College of Rheumatology classification criteria, a score of ≥6 on the SLEDAI-200019 and a positive test result for antinuclear antibodies were eligible for the study. Some patients given were the epitope every 2 weeks instead of every 4 weeks.
Assay - Comments: Patients treated with the epitope showed  significant improvement in physician’s global assessment  and SLE Disease Activity Index (SLEDAI) scores. Patients given the epitope every 2 weeks also showed improvement, but not as much as those injected every 4 weeks.  At weeks 12 and 24, a clinical response was already evident for the group treated every 4 weeks.

Reference - Authors: Li Zhang; Anne M Bertucci; Rosalind Ramsey-Goldman; Elizabeth Randall Harsha-Strong; Richard K Burt; Syamal K Datta
Reference - Title: Major pathogenic steps in human lupus can be effectively suppressed by nucleosomal histone peptide epitope-induced regulatory immunity.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence is found in Datta, SK,  Ann N Y Acad Sci. 2003 Apr;987:79-90 [PMID: 12727626].
Immunization - Comments: PBMC from patients with active lupus were studied.
Assay - Comments: Treatment of PBMC from patients with inactive lupus with the epitope led to an increase of Treg cells. Cells from patients with active lupus required the addition of dexamethasone for the increase to be seen.

Epitope - Synonyms: (9Z)-octadec-9-enoic acid, (9Z)-Octadecenoic acid, (Z)-Octadec-9-enoic acid, 18:1 n-9, 18:1Delta9cis, C18:1 n-9, cis-9-octadecenoic acid, cis-Delta(9)-octadecenoic acid, cis-oleic acid, FA 18:1, Octadec-9-enoic acid, Oelsaeure, Oleate, Oleic acid, OLEIC ACID
Immunization - Comments: The CD1a-restricted BK6 T cell clone was isolated from a patient with systemic lupus erythematosus and is described in the cited reference: Porcelli et al. (1989) Nature 341(6241):447-450 [PMID: 2477705]. Jurkat T cells were transfected with the BK6 TCR alpha and beta chains.
Assay - Location of Assay Data in Refere: Figures 4, 5, 7, Table 1, Supplementary Figures 3, 4 and PDB 4X6D
Assay - Comments: The crystal structure of the BK6 TCR bound to the endogenous lipid/CD1a complex was determined by molecular replacement. The electron density in the A' pocket for the BK6 TCR-CD1a-endo structure was modeled with oleic acid due to evidence from mass spectroscopy indicative of multiple lipids with C18:1 lipid tails and consistency with observed electron density.
